David King, Principal

ARRSD Fall Reopening Survey (Please fill out a new survey for each child in your home.)

Athol-Royalston Regional School District
July 16 at 4:05 PM Â·

Dear Parent/Guardian,



As you may be aware, the Athol-Royalston Regional School District is planning for a full reopening of school this fall. This means that students will return to school as close as possible to the normal date in late August.



In order to ensure the district can meet safety regulations put forth by the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education, we must gather information on each of your children. Please fill out this survey using a new survey for each child who attends ARRSD schools by no later than July 30, 2020.



Survey link:

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSeX9utCXkUwLOYM_Ca9LKm0RCuC2wV_I1_JXJ_sngvMOV6mJw/viewform?usp=sf_link



Thank you for taking the time to fill out this survey. It is truly appreciated. Your responses will help the district to plan an appropriate school program for your child this fall.

shared_text:
Assumption University Cross Country and Track & Field
June 29 at 4:05 PM Â·

Todayâ€™s Senior Spotlight is Emily Casella from Athol, MA. Emily, a human services and rehab studies major was one of our team captains in the throws group. Emily competed in all the throwing events (shot put, discus, javelin, hammer/weight) which led to being named the 2019 Most Outstanding Field Performer after scoring 30 points at the NE10 Outdoor Championship Meet. She leaves holding school records in shotput (indoor and outdoor), discus, and hammer.

AHS Students and Families

The AHS staff has left Athol High School on the way towards your house with your Swag Bag. We will knock on your door and ring the door bell, place Swag Bag on the doorstep with your Report Card. Our staff member will then step back away from the door and wait to see if anyone answers the door. If no one is at home, we will pull back the Report Card and place it in the mail early next week. We hope you enjoy your Swag Bag gifts and wish everyone a safe and happy summer.

Re: Remote Learning Survey Results
Date: June 17, 2020

A survey was sent out to families in early June to gather information on the remote learning experience. The district received 542 completed surveys. To view the results of the survey, please click the picture below.

The feedback provided gives us important information as we look into planning for next school year. The district will be analyzing this data and providing a response, including next steps, in early July. A follow-up memo will be posted at that time. Thank you for your participation completing this survey. Your input and suggestions are so very important as we work on planning for the 2020-2021 school year.

post_text:
Dear Athol High School Underclassmen

This year has been anything but normal. The faculty, staff and administration at Athol High School couldn't be more proud of the grit and determination that you have shown through these most trying times. You have met our challenge with completing your coursework and final exams with great attention and care for your own academic success. Today we celebrate you for rising to that challenge, acknowledging your Raider Pride and recognizing that we are #allinthistogether. We hope you enjoy this video tribute to you. Lastly, please be on the look for one of our faculty members tomorrow morning (Thursday June 18th) between 10:30 AM and 12:00 PM. We will be delivering a Swag Bag to each of your home addresses. Enjoy the summer and we look forward to seeing each of you in late August.

Athol High School

FINAL EXAM NOTICE

This is a friendly reminder for our students and families that the final exam period has begun. Based on our Remote Learning document, all students are required to complete a final exam in each class. For clarification, even if a student has met the requirement for passing at least two terms; final exams must be completed and turned in for students to get credit for the course.

Final exams for all classes have been emailed to each student and copies of the exams are also posted on each teacherâ€™s Online Learning page. (http://www.arrsd.org/ahs-online-learning/) If there is any difficulty accessing the exam, please contact the teacher directly through email.

As always, if you have any further concerns, please feel free to reach out to me through email, or by contacting my office at 978-249-2435.
David King, Principal
dking@arrsd.org
(978) 249-2435

Based on our Remote Learning document, all students are required to complete a final exam in each class. For clarification, even if a student has met the requirement for passing at least two terms; final exams must be completed and turned in for students to get credit for the course.

Final exams for all classes have been emailed to each student and copies of the exams are also posted on each teacherâ€™s Online Learning page. (http://www.arrsd.org/ahs-online-learning/) If there is any difficulty accessing the exam, please contact the teacher directly through email.

As always, if you have any further concerns, please feel free to reach out to me through email, or by contacting my office at 978-249-2435.
David King, Principal
dking@arrsd.org
(978) 249-2435

post_text: A message from one of our seniors, shared with her permission. We miss you all! #raiderpride #classof2020
shared_text:
Taylor Cleveland
April 1 at 3:39 PM Â·

To my fellow classmates,
this is certainly not how we thought we would experience our senior year. Time for us has been cut short. Senior year is very emotional because itâ€™s a bitter sweet ending to a huge chapter in our lives. I wish you all the best and hope every single one of you accomplish your dreams in life. i wish nothing but happiness and safety to all my peers. I hope one day we can look back at these times and remember what it was like. We all have complained on how we canâ€™t wait to get out of these long halls and yellow colored classrooms but as i sit here in my house for almost two weeks with no contact with anyone besides snapchat, ft, and texting i regret the times i have complained about school. our pep rallyâ€™s, lip sync, even mid terms. Hopefully we will be able to go back in May like they say, so we can enjoy our last couple of weeks in athol high.

â€œThe future belongs to those who believe in the beauty of their dreamsâ€ -Eleanor Roosevelt

post_text:
Adjusting to the new â€œnormalâ€ caused by this pandemic has caused an increase in stress, anxiety and sadness for most individuals.

For our students, this may be causing feelings of isolation, uncertainty, or frustration due to schools being closed and being forced to stay home. We are all grieving the loss of physically being able to see family and friends, the loss of our daily routines, and loss of â€œfreedomâ€ in our lives. Itâ€™s okay to not feel okay right now.

During these times, tele health services are still available to help in any way that we can. We are currently enrolling new students and families in our program.

If you are interested in counseling or support, please reach out to Rebekah Manseau at (978) 514-3796 to book an appointment.

post_text:
Last year the AHS Music Department held its first Mattress Showroom Fundraiser. On March 22nd the fundraising division of Mattress Firm will be coming back and setting up a showroom in the cafe. The showroom consists of roughly 25 different displays that you can try out. They sell pillows, mattress protectors, etc. You can place an order that day and have it delivered to your house in a few weeks. Last year we raised $1000 for the Music Department.

If you could, please share this information with as many people as possible. If you are in need of a new bed or know of someone that might be interested please share this out. Even if you don't, let people know about it.

post_text:
A group of 9th graders attended a tour of Fitchburg State University today. To date 80% of the Class of 2023 has gone on a college tour. Plans are in the works for students that have not attended yet.

The feedback from students was overwhelmingly positive. One student remarked, "I never thought I would ever go to college. After this trip, I can see myself here. College is so different than school."

post_text:
The last few weeks at AHS have been busy.

Eric Moss wowed 7th -12th grade students with his strongman experience. He bent a frying pan, a horseshoe and a reinforced steel bar (on the bridge of his nose). His message was one of hope and a growth mind set. If we believe that we can do challenging things, then we will have amazing accomplishments.

Terrance White, from Sandy Hook Promise, provided all of our students with the program Start with Hello. Three simple steps can help everyone feel a sense of connection. 1. See someone alone 2. Reach out and help 3. Start with Hello. Many thanks to the MA Attorney Generalâ€™s Office and Sandy Hook Promise.

We recognized many of our students who have perfect attendance. They participated in fun minute to win it challenges.

On the half day, teachers and para professionals worked hard and challenged one another as we work together to improve our school culture.

We had a family mentioned that they received the onecall this evening but did not get the message. here is a transcription of the message for any other family that might not have received the message:

Good evening this is David King, Principal of Athol High School. on behalf of our entire staff we want to thank our students and families for the positive transition of YONDR in our classrooms. Students deserve this commitment to reclaim the educational space of our classroom and making them free of cell phone distractions. we truly do understand this is a big adjustment for all but are guided in the belief that these steps will produce a teaching and learning environment that we all can be proud of and will prepare our students for life beyond Athol High School.In the coming days we will be providing additional information that supports this transition phrase. This information will be emailed and posted on our school's website. As always if you would like to discuss further please contact me at (978) 249-2435

Thank you and have a good evening

shared_text:
Celebrating Schools in the Athol Royalston Regional School District added 137 new photos to the album: Athol Triumphs Over Easthampton in Playoffs!
June 7, 2019 at 5:09 PM Â·

Athol Triumphs Over Easthampton in Playoffs! Photographs and Story by MItchell R. Grosky

Athol's Varsity Baseball Team combined superb pitching, great defense, and timely hitting to advance in the playoffs by earning a suspenseful 1-0 victory over the Easthampton Eagles. Mark Ferrari gave up only 4 hits, and sent 15 Eagles away with strikeouts. The Red Raiders now advance to the Division 3 quarterfinals which will be on Monday. Bryce King scored the winning run after getting a single and stealing second base. Congratulations to all the players, to Coach Josh Talbot and the entire coaching staff.

I enjoyed the experience of not only watching the game as a fan and cheering on our Red Raiders, but also trying my best to document the action with my camera. I picked up some good pointers from Athol Daily News/Greenfield Recorder Photographer Mike Phillips, as we viewed the game together. Thanks, Mike!

All photographs by Mitchell R. Grosky. Should you share any photos on facebook, please respect the copyright by crediting the photographer.

During our recent renovations of the High School we came across a wallet belonging to a Jeffrey L. Hart. From the library card located in the wallet it seems he lived off White Pond Road.

Looking at the pictures in the wallet he had many pictures of friends leaving him notes dated around 1968-1969.There also seemed to be some family pictures.

Please help us in locating and reuniting Jeffrey with his lost wallet

post_text:
Recent studies have shown that at least 1 in 5 of our youth are struggling with mental health concerns. There is such a high need for treatment among adolescents, however, the long waitlists and shortages of providers has left most of this vulnerable population without care. The good news is that tele behavioral health has been helping to bridge this gap. We have immediate openings here at Athol High and the students are able to access our services during the school day to alleviate concerns of distance, busy schedules, and/or transportation issues.

Please contact guidance at (978)249-2436 if you or your child is interested in this service

As part of our Attendance Matters campaign, we would like to recognize the 21 students at Athol High School that have perfect attendance through Winter Break.
Jasmine Adams, Cassidy Baumann, Grace Dufour, Amanda Fuller, Justin Giansanto, Joselyn Gleason-Beach, Joseph Gray, Nathan Heath, Alexis Her, Logan Hume, Ava LeBlanc, Sadey Lehtomaki, Connor Mahony, Raven Malcolm, Shannyn Moulton, Quentin Polana, Reily Polana, Sophie Putnam, Vivien Sacco-Rosado, Isabelle Spooner, and Matthew Willhite

On behalf of the administration and staff, we would like to acknowledge your outstanding dedication and commitment to our core value of DETERMINATION in making it to school everyday.
All 21 students were entered into a drawing for our Subway Student of the Week lunch which includes a 6" sub, cookie and fountain drink. The winner of the drawing was senior Jasmine Adams.

As part of our Attendance Matters campaign, we would like to recognize the 21 students at Athol High School that have perfect attendance through Winter Break.
Jasmine Adams, Cassidy Baumann, Grace Dufour, Amanda Fuller, Justin Giansanto, Joselyn Gleason-Beach, Joseph Gray, Nathan Heath, Alexis Her, Logan Hume, Ava LeBlanc, Sadey Lehtomaki, Connor Mahony, Raven Malcolm, Shannyn Moulton, Quentin Polana, Reily Polana, Sophie Putnam, Vivien Sacco-Rosado, Isabelle Spooner, and Matthew Willhite

On behalf of the administration and staff, we would like to acknowledge your outstanding dedication and commitment to our core value of DETERMINATION in making it to school everyday.
All 21 students were entered into a drawing for our Subway Student of the Week lunch which includes a 6" sub, cookie and fountain drink. The winner of the drawing was senior Jasmine Adams.
